04272nam a22006255i 9780691211213DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021944420  a97806912112137 a10.1515/97806912112132doi  a(DE-B1597)589122  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBF575.G7bC475 2021 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a155.9372231 aCholbi, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGrief :bA Philosophical Guide /cMichael Cholbi. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. For Whom We Grieve -- tChapter 2. What to Expect When You’re Grieving -- tChapter 3. Finding Ourselves in Grief -- tChapter 4. Making Good on the Pain -- tChapter 5. Reason in the Midst of Grieving -- tChapter 6. Our Duty to Grieve -- tChapter 7. Madness and Medicine -- tConclusion. Grief Most Human -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn engaging and illuminating exploration of grief—and why, despite its intense pain, it can also help us growExperiencing grief at the death of a person we love or who matters to us—as universal as it is painful—is central to the human condition. Surprisingly, however, philosophers have rarely examined grief in any depth. In Grief, Michael Cholbi presents a groundbreaking philosophical exploration of this complex emotional event, offering valuable new insights about what grief is, whom we grieve, and how grief can ultimately lead us to a richer self-understanding and a fuller realization of our humanity.Drawing on psychology, social science, and literature as well as philosophy, Cholbi explains that we grieve for the loss of those in whom our identities are invested, including people we cherish without personally knowing, such as public figures. Their deaths not only deprive us of worthwhile experiences; they also disrupt our commitments and values. Yet grief is something we should embrace rather than avoid, an important part of a good and meaningful life. The key to understanding this paradox, Cholbi says, is that grief offers us a unique and powerful opportunity to grow in self-knowledge by fashioning a new identity. Although grief can be tumultuous and disorienting, it also reflects our distinctly human capacity to rationally adapt as the relationships we depend on evolve.An original account of how grieving works and why it is so important, Grief shows how the pain of this experience gives us a chance to deepen our relationships with others and ourselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aGriefxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073912140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691211213zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691211213423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691211213/original  a978-3-11-073912-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK